# ScopeLock Project Rules

## Core principles
- Keep the codebase small, boring, and easy to inspect manually.
- Prefer the simplest implementation that satisfies the requirement.
- Do not add features, files, abstractions, dependencies, or configuration unless explicitly required.
- Default to the simplest viable implementation. Future-proof only when it directly supports an approved near-term requirement, and explain that choice to the user.
- Do not refactor unrelated code.

## Instruction discipline
- Follow the exact task requested and nothing more.
- If a requirement is ambiguous, choose the simpler interpretation.
- Do not silently expand scope.
- Do not replace existing patterns unless there is a clear bug or explicit instruction.

## File discipline
- Do not create new files unless they are necessary to complete the requested task.
- Before creating a new file, check whether the logic belongs in an existing file.
- Prefer fewer files over more files when reasonable.
- Do not rename, move, or split files unless explicitly requested.
- Do not leave behind unused files, duplicate files, or placeholder files.

## Dependency discipline
- Do not add packages unless absolutely necessary.
- Prefer built-in platform/browser/TypeScript/React capabilities first.
- If a package seems useful but is not strictly required, do not add it.
- If adding a dependency is unavoidable, explain why.

## Architecture discipline
- Keep domain logic separate from UI logic.
- Business/domain logic must be reusable and must not depend on React components.
- Agreement/document generation must exist as a pure function.
- Keep data types/schema definitions centralized and consistent.
- Prefer plain functions and simple components over elaborate patterns.

## State management
- Use simple local state by default.
- Do not introduce Redux, Zustand, context-heavy patterns, or custom state frameworks unless explicitly requested.
- Avoid unnecessary indirection in state flow.

## UI discipline
- Optimize for mobile-first usability.
- Keep UI components simple, readable, and easy to edit.
- Do not add visual complexity, animation libraries, or design systems unless explicitly requested.
- Prioritize function over polish.
- Co-locate styles with the page or component that owns them.
- Keep `src/App.css` limited to design tokens, app shell/layout primitives, shared utility classes, print/PDF globals, and other truly global rules.
- Do not add new page-specific or feature-specific styles to `src/App.css`.
- New pages and major components should import their own CSS file (for example `ComponentName.tsx` + `ComponentName.css`).
- If a style is only used by one page or component, it belongs with that page or component.

## Type safety and consistency
- Do not invent fields not present in the canonical schema.
- Keep field names consistent across:
  - types
  - form state
  - sample data
  - generator logic
  - rendered output
- Do not leave dead fields, unused props, or mismatched names.
- Prefer explicit TypeScript types over loose typing.

## Hallucination prevention
- Do not claim code works unless it is consistent with the visible codebase.
- Do not invent files, imports, functions, routes, APIs, or dependencies that do not exist.
- Do not reference environment variables, backend services, or persistence layers unless they are actually implemented.
- Do not assume hidden infrastructure.

## Editing behavior
- Make the minimum necessary change.
- Prefer surgical diffs over broad rewrites.
- Preserve working code unless there is a concrete reason to change it.
- When fixing something, avoid incidental cleanup outside the task unless it is directly relevant.

## Output behavior
- Summarize what changed clearly.
- Call out any assumptions.
- If something could not be completed exactly as requested, say so directly.
- Do not pretend uncertainty does not exist.

## Quality checks before finishing
Before concluding any task, verify:
- no unnecessary files were added
- no unnecessary dependencies were added
- no unrelated code was changed
- no field names are inconsistent
- no broken imports were introduced
- no dead code or placeholder code remains
- architecture rules were preserved
- output matches the requested scope

## Product-specific rules
- This product is a mobile-first welder job agreement generator.
- Agreements must remain short, plain-language, and practical.
- Do not turn the agreement into a large corporate subcontract.
- Do not add legal-advice features.
- Shared utility logic belongs in `src/lib/`; do not duplicate small helper functions across multiple files when one shared utility would keep behavior consistent.
- HTML escaping must come from a shared utility (`src/lib/html-escape.ts`) rather than repeated inline `esc()` / `escapeHtml()` implementations.
- Keep generated agreements focused on:
  - scope of work
  - exclusions
  - hidden damage
  - third-party responsibility
  - change orders
  - payment terms
  - completion and liability transfer
  - workmanship warranty
